title: Life-threatening parvovirus outbreak sparks warnings from Logan City Council | Quest News
text:
Life-threatening parvovirus outbreak sparks warnings from Logan City Council Sarah Orr, Quest Newspapers February 22, 2017 1:42pm 
TWO cases of the deadly parvovirus have been confirmed in a southeast suburb, prompting urgent calls for vaccinations. 
A Logan City Council spokeswoman said both cases occurred in Eagleby during the past week. 
The life-threatening disease is known to spread rapidly and can be carried by humans who have been in contact with the highly-contagious particles. 
Animals, Parks, and City Standards Committee chairwoman Jennie Breene said dog owners should seek immediate veterinary attention if symptoms appear. 
“This could be lethargy, a lack of appetite, abdominal pain, fever, vomiting, and diarrhoea, often with blood,” she said. 
“The virus can survive for long periods and there often isn’t an obvious source of infection, with clinical signs generally appearing four to ten days after infection.” 
Faecal sample tests can provide answers within just ten minutes. 
Puppies, unvaccinated dogs and those who have not received a booster shot are most at risk however dogs of all ages and breeds can be affected. 
Immunisation can cost between $80 to $110, a small price to pay considering treatment starts at $1000. Most viewed
